{"id":"1407.4689","submitter":"John D. Swain","authors":"M. Alvermann, Y. N. Srivastava, J. Swain and A. Widom","title":"Biological Electric Fields and Rate Equations for Biophotons","comments":"6 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph q-bio.OT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Ultraweak bioluminescence - the emission of biophotons - remains an\nexperimentally well-established, but theoretically poorly understood\nphenomenon. This paper presents several related investigations into the\nphysical process of both spontaneous biophoton emission and delayed\nluminescence. Since light intensities depend upon the modulus squared of their\ncorresponding electric fields we first make some general estimates about the\ninherent electric fields within various biological systems. Since photon\nemission from living matter following an initial excitation (\"delayed\nluminescence\") typically does not follow a simple exponential decay law after\nexcitation we discuss such non-exponential decays from a general theoretical\nperspective and argue that they are often to be expected and why. We then\ndiscuss the dynamics behind some nonlinear rate equations, connecting them both\nto biological growth rates and biophoton emission rates, noting a possible\nconnection with cancer. We then return to non-exponential decay laws seen for\ndelayed luminescence in an experimental context and again note a possible\nconnection with cancer.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 13 Apr 2014 23:44:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-07-18"}
